            <div id="pageTitle">Stages of an Interview </div>
            <div id="ContentText">Every interview ideally consists of five stages namely, building rapport, introductory, core, confirmation, and closing. Each stage has a specific purpose and takes up an approximate percentage of the interview.
                <div>Click each <b><strong>stage</strong></b> to learn more.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="greytext">The Interview Process – Stages of an Interview</div>
            
            <div id="canvas">
                <div class="poptab" id="poptab_1" rel="popcnt_1" audio_name=""><div>Building Rapport</div></div>
                <div class="poptab" id="poptab_2" rel="popcnt_2" audio_name=""><div style=" margin-left:7px;">Introductory</div></div>
                <div class="poptab" id="poptab_3" rel="popcnt_3" audio_name=""><div style=" margin-left:-9px;">Core</div></div>
                <div class="poptab" id="poptab_4" rel="popcnt_4" audio_name=""><div style=" margin-left:-18px;">Confirmation</div></div>
                <div class="poptab" id="poptab_5" rel="popcnt_5" audio_name=""><div style=" margin-left:-16px;">Closing</div></div>
                
                <div id="bf_quote1"></div>
                
              <div class="popcontent" id="popcnt_1">
                    Building rapport is the first step to a successful interview and represents a meagre but important part of the interview. <br>
                    <strong><b><i>Time allocated: 2 minutes</i></b></strong><br><br>
                    <b><strong><i>Purpose:</i></strong></b>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Warm up and ease the candidate into the interview process.</li>
                        <li>Identify the format for the rest of the interview. </li>
                        <li>Build a rapport with candidates. </li>
                    </ul>
                    <strong><b><i>Examples:</i></b></strong>
                    <ul>
                    	<li>“I’m glad the construction activity on the highway didn"t keep you from coming in this morning.”</li>
                    	<li>“How are you liking the weather today?”</li>
                    	<li>Do you need water?</li>
					</ul>

                </div>
                
                <div class="popcontent" id="popcnt_2">
                    This stage represents the introductory phase of the interview.<br>
                    <strong><i><b>Time allocated: 3 minutes</b></i></strong><br><br>
                    <strong><i><b>Purpose:</b></i></strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Initiate your assessment process.</li>
                        <li>Ask questions about topics familiar to the candidates  to avoid undue pressure.</li>
                        <li>Ask questions that are broad enough to generate additional questions by you.</li>
                        <li>Allow the candidates to relax and articulate their thoughts better. </li>
                    </ul>
                    <strong><i><b>Examples:</b></i></strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>“What five adjectives describe you best?”</li>
                        <li>“How did you find out about this job?”</li>
                        <li>“What interests you most about this position?”</li>
                    </ul>

                </div>
                
                
                <div class="popcontent" id="popcnt_3">
                    You are ready to move on to the crucial core stage of the interview.<br>
                    <strong><i><b>Time allocated: 30 minutes</b></i></strong><br><br>
                    <strong><i><b>The primary purpose of this stage is to:</b></i></strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Gather the bulk of your information about the candidate.</li>
                        <li>Ask enough of the right open-ended questions.</li>
                        <li>Evaluate the candidate for core skills, technical or functional skills, personality etc.</li>
                        <li>Provide information, and answer questions from the candidate.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <strong><i><b>Examples:</b></i></strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>“Give me an example of a problem you've had at school and how you solved it.”</li>
                        <li>“Are your grades a good measure of your ability?”</li>
                        <li>“What makes a job enjoyable for you?”</li>
                    </ul>


                </div>
            
            	<div class="popcontent" id="popcnt_4">
                    The confirmation stage, represents verification phase of the interview.<br>
                    <strong><i><b>Time allocated: 5 minutes</b></i></strong><br><br>
                    <strong><i><b>The primary purpose of this stage is to:</b></i></strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Verify information gathered thus far about and from candidates.</li> 
                        <li>Emphasis on open-ended questions  that help validate information gathered from the candidate.</li>  
                        <li>Keep closed-ended questions to the minimum.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <strong><i><b>Examples:</b></i></strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>“You mentioned that you were not allowed to grow in the previous job. What you mean by that?”</li>
                        <li>“You stated that you are leaving your job for a better opportunity. Can you please elaborate? ”</li>
                        <li>“Tell me more about how your new job responsibilities will differ from the earlier one. ”</li>
                    </ul>


                </div>
                
                <div class="popcontent" id="popcnt_5">
                    Closing is the final stage of the interview. <br>
                    <strong><i><b>Time allocated: 5 minutes</b></i></strong><br><br>
                    <strong><i><b>The primary purpose of this stage is to:</b></i></strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Ensure that you have covered all relevant areas.</li>
                        <li>Inform the candidate of the next steps. </li>
                        <li>Provide constructive feedback to the candidate for the actual interview.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <strong><i><b>Examples:</b></i></strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>“What else can you tell me about your decision to choose this field?”</li>
                        <li>“Share any additional examples of how you dealt with difficult people.”</li>
                        <li>“What personal development are you expecting from the job you are applying to?”</li>
                    </ul>

                </div>
            </div> 
            
               
